abstract: Killing of San Francisco Police Officer Isaac Espinoza has placed capital punishment at center of political and emotional storm that has some people asking whether different standard should be applied in case of law enforcement officials killed on job; it has also placed Dist Atty Kamala D Harris, first black woman to be elected district attorney in California, in standoff with Police Dept and Espinoza's family over principle that she considers non-negotiable; Harris says her opposition to capital punishment is partly based on its being applied disproportionately to members of minority groups; David Hill has been charged with Espinoza's murder; photos (M)
snippet: Killing of San Francisco Police Officer Isaac Espinoza has placed capital punishment at center of political and emotional storm that has some people asking whether different standard should be applied in case of law enforcement officials killed on...
lead_paragraph: Opinion polls show that San Franciscans overwhelmingly oppose the death penalty, and in her winning campaign for district attorney last fall, Kamala D. Harris made no secret of her strong opposition as well.

abstract: From local lounges to concert halls, New Years Eve is the occasion to crank up both the volume and the price. A list of musical events.
snippet: From local lounges to concert halls, New Years Eve is the occasion to crank up both the volume and the price. A list of musical events.
lead_paragraph: New Year's Eve isn't just a calendar date; it's an industry, a full-employment program for makers of Champagne, party hats and toothpicks, for waiters and taxi drivers and bouncers, and not least for disc jockeys and musicians. The urge to greet the new year with public songs and dancing may well be primordial, and from local lounges to concert halls, in places that have music every night and places that don't, New Year's Eve is the occasion to crank up both the volume and the price. In New York City the night's offerings run from introspective songwriters to jazz swingers to jam bands to thumping, pulsating dance music. In most cases it's a good idea to make reservations or buy tickets in advance. (* denotes a highly recommended performance; New Year's Eve cabaret shows are listed on Page 44.)

abstract: A selective listing by Times critics of new or noteworthy opera, classical music and dance events this weekend in the Northeast.    Opera    ''EUGENE ONEGIN.'' The work of Valery Gergiev and the Kirov Orchestra can be frustratingly uneven. But as the Kirov Opera's three-week residency at the Metropolitan Opera House, part of the Lincoln Center Festival, has proven so far, Mr. Gergiev and his company bring matchless authority to the Russian operatic repertory. Tomorrow night they offer the first of four festival performances of Tchaikovsky's ''Eugene Onegin,'' which may be the Russian opera best known in the West. Still it should be fascinating to experience the Kirov's production, which stars the baritone Vladimir Moroz in the title role, the tenor Yevgeny Akimov as Lenski and the soprano Irina Mataeva as Tatiana. Tomorrow night at 8, Metropolitan Opera House, (212) 362-6000. Tickets: $35 to $150 (Anthony Tommasini).

abstract: Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts for this weekend and New Year's Eve. * denotes a highly recommended performance.    This Weekend    GEORGE COLEMAN QUARTET, Smoke, 2751 Broadway, at 106th Street, (212) 864-6662. Mr. Coleman's broad, rich tenor saxophone tone was first widely noticed with Miles Davis's band in the early 1960's and then on some great Blue Note albums, including Herbie Hancock's ''Maiden Voyage''; he still has a capacious sound and a nose-to-the-grindstone drive. Tonight and tomorrow night at 9, 11 and 12:30; cover charge is $20 (Ben Ratliff).
